<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Souring" class="currentChild" href="Souring">Souring</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A printing defect that occurs in <a title="Flexography" href="Flexography">flexography</a> or <a title="Screen Printing" href="Screen_Printing">screen printing</a> with <a title="Nitrocellulose" href="Nitrocellulose">nitrocellulose</a>-based inks utilizing <a title="Hygroscopic" href="Hygroscopic">hygroscopic</a> (absorbing moisture readily) <a title="Solvent" href="Solvent">solvent</a>s, in which the nitrocellulose, being water-insoluble, precipitates out of the ink when the solvent picks up water from the atmosphere. Although the addition of other substances (such as <a title="Ester" href="Ester">ester</a>s) will help alleviate the problem, the best defense against souring is to minimize the exposure of the ink to humid environments by using lids and fountain covers, or to use a small amount of ink in the ink fountain and refresh the ink often. 
</p>
